{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638202"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17697"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72110"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57580"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10412"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24359"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72110"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESalt taste perception is essential for maintaining appropriate sodium intake and fluid balance in the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism for salt taste detection on the tongue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sodium ions trigger calcium release from internal stores","Sodium ions enter taste cells through epithelial sodium channels","Sodium ions form complexes with taste receptor proteins","Sodium ions bind to G-protein coupled receptors","Sodium ions activate voltage-gated potassium channels"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium ions enter taste cells through epithelial sodium channels (ENaC)\u003C/strong\u003E located on the apical membrane of taste receptor cells. This direct entry of sodium ions leads to depolarisation of the cell and subsequent neurotransmitter release, allowing salt taste perception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium ions trigger calcium release from internal stores\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcium signalling may occur downstream, this is not the primary mechanism for initial salt detection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium ions form complexes with taste receptor proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Salt taste relies on direct ion flow through channels rather than complex formation with proteins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium ions bind to G-protein coupled receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - While other taste qualities use G-protein coupled receptors, salt taste primarily utilises ion channels.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium ions activate voltage-gated potassium channels\u003C/strong\u003E - These channels contribute to taste cell repolarisation but are not the primary sensors for salt taste.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe importance of epithelial sodium channels in salt taste is demonstrated by the fact that amiloride, an ENaC blocker, significantly reduces salt taste perception.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Salt taste is primarily detected by epithelial sodium channels (ENaC) on the tongue.","Amiloride blocks epithelial sodium channels and reduces salt taste perception.","Salt receptors are located on the apical membrane of taste receptor cells in taste buds."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57580"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57580"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:39:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:40:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10411"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72110"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":